#: ../../../faq.md:1
msgid "Frequently Asked Questions"
msgstr "常見問題"

#: ../../../faq.md:3
msgid ""
"The most common questions and issues users face are aggregated to this FAQ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:11
msgid "Why spaces? I prefer tabs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:13
msgid ""
"PEP 8 recommends spaces over tabs, and they are used by most of the Python "
"community. _Black_ provides no options to configure the indentation style, "
"and requests for such options will not be considered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:17
msgid ""
"However, we recognise that using tabs is an accessibility issue as well. "
"While the option will never be added to _Black_, visually impaired "
"developers may find conversion tools such as `expand/unexpand` (for Linux) "
"useful when contributing to Python projects. A workflow might consist of e."
"g. setting up appropriate pre-commit and post-merge git hooks, and scripting "
"`unexpand` to run after applying _Black_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:23
msgid "Does Black have an API?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:25
msgid ""
"Not yet. _Black_ is fundamentally a command line tool. Many [integrations](/"
"integrations/index.md) are provided, but a Python interface is not one of "
"them. A simple API is being [planned](https://github.com/psf/black/"
"issues/779) though."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:30
msgid "Is Black safe to use?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:32
msgid ""
"Yes. _Black_ is strictly about formatting, nothing else. Black strives to "
"ensure that after formatting the AST is [checked](the_black_code_style/"
"current_style.md#ast-before-and-after-formatting) with limited special cases "
"where the code is allowed to differ. If issues are found, an error is raised "
"and the file is left untouched. Magical comments that influence linters and "
"other tools, such as `# noqa`, may be moved by _Black_. See below for more "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:39
msgid "How stable is Black's style?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:41
msgid ""
"Stable. _Black_ aims to enforce one style and one style only, with some room "
"for pragmatism. See [The Black Code Style](the_black_code_style/index.md) "
"for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:44
msgid ""
"Starting in 2022, the formatting output is stable for the releases made in "
"the same year (other than unintentional bugs). At the beginning of every "
"year, the first release will make changes to the stable style. It is "
"possible to opt in to the latest formatting styles using the `--preview` "
"flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:49
msgid "Why is my file not formatted?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:51
msgid ""
"Most likely because it is ignored in `.gitignore` or excluded with "
"configuration. See [file collection and discovery](usage_and_configuration/"
"file_collection_and_discovery.md) for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:55
msgid "Why is my Jupyter Notebook cell not formatted?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:57
msgid ""
"_Black_ is timid about formatting Jupyter Notebooks. Cells containing any of "
"the following will not be formatted:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:60
msgid "automagics (e.g. `pip install black`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:61
msgid "non-Python cell magics (e.g. `%%writefile`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:62
msgid "multiline magics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:63
msgid "code which `IPython`'s `TransformerManager` would transform magics into"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:64
msgid "invalid syntax"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:66
msgid ""
"See [Using _Black_ with Jupyter Notebooks](guides/"
"using_black_with_jupyter_notebooks.md#cells-that-black-will-skip) for "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:70
msgid "Why does Flake8 report warnings?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:72
msgid ""
"Some of Flake8's rules conflict with Black's style. We recommend disabling "
"these rules. See [Using _Black_ with other tools](labels/why-pycodestyle-"
"warnings)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:75
msgid "Which Python versions does Black support?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:77
msgid ""
"_Black_ generally supports all Python versions supported by CPython (see "
"[the Python devguide](https://devguide.python.org/versions/) for current "
"information). We promise to support at least all Python versions that have "
"not reached their end of life. This is the case for both running _Black_ and "
"formatting code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:82
msgid ""
"Support for formatting Python 2 code was removed in version 22.0. While "
"we've made no plans to stop supporting older Python 3 minor versions "
"immediately, their support might also be removed some time in the future "
"without a deprecation period."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:86
msgid ""
"`await`/`async` as soft keywords/identifiers are no longer supported as of "
"25.9.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:88
msgid ""
"Runtime support for 3.6 was removed in version 22.10.0, for 3.7 in version "
"23.7.0, for 3.8 in version 24.10.0, and for 3.9 in version 25.12.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:91
msgid "Why does my linter or typechecker complain after I format my code?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:93
msgid ""
"Some linters and other tools use magical comments (e.g., `# noqa`, `# type: "
"ignore`) to influence their behavior. While Black does its best to recognize "
"such comments and leave them in the right place, this detection is not and "
"cannot be perfect. Therefore, you'll sometimes have to manually move these "
"comments to the right place after you format your codebase with _Black_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:99
msgid "Can I run Black with PyPy?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:101
msgid "Yes, there is support for PyPy 3.8 and higher."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:103
msgid "Why does Black not detect syntax errors in my code?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:105
msgid ""
"_Black_ is an autoformatter, not a Python linter or interpreter. Detecting "
"all syntax errors is not a goal. It can format all code accepted by CPython "
"(if you find an example where that doesn't hold, please report a bug!), but "
"it may also format some code that CPython doesn't accept."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:112
msgid "What is `compiled: yes/no` all about in the version output?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:114
msgid ""
"While _Black_ is indeed a pure Python project, we use [mypyc] to compile "
"_Black_ into a C Python extension, usually doubling performance. These "
"compiled wheels are available for 64-bit versions of Windows (both AMD and "
"ARM), Linux (via the manylinux standard), and macOS across all supported "
"CPython versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:119
msgid ""
"Platforms including musl-based and/or ARM Linux distributions are currently "
"**not** supported. These platforms will fall back to the slower pure Python "
"wheel available on PyPI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:123
msgid ""
"If you are experiencing exceptionally weird issues or even segfaults, you "
"can try passing `--no-binary black` to your pip install invocation. This "
"flag excludes all wheels (including the pure Python wheel), so this command "
"will use the [sdist]."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:131
msgid "Why are emoji not displaying correctly on Windows?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:133
msgid ""
"When using Windows, the emoji in _Black_'s output may not display correctly. "
"This is not fixable from _Black_'s end."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.md:136
msgid ""
"Instead, run your chosen command line/shell through [Windows Terminal], "
"which will properly handle rendering the emoji."
msgstr ""
